      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-9">
        <h2>Exploration of Twitter Data Use in Transport Disruption Research</h2>
        <p>
        We are researching social media data in the context of transport disruption, using the Glasgow Commonwealth Games as a case study for planned and unplanned disruption. The project will directly address OECD Challenge 1 (reliability, validity and generalisability of new forms of data) and Challenge 3 (new forms of personal data and its transparency) by developing and propagating data mining and dissemination models in partnership with publc transport agencies. We also build upon research conducted in the dot.rural Informed Rural Passenger Project. We anticipate that this research will inform creativity and innovation in disruption planning and response strategies by impacted agencies, as well as responding to ESRC&acirc;&euro;&trade;s strategic priority of Influencing Behaviour and Informing interventions.

        </p>
        <h3>Research Questions</h3>
        <p>How can we develop more effective intervention strategies using socal mdia both as a platform for public communication, and as a rich source of data for understanding the passenger experience on a variety of transport modes? How can we develop more effective long-term approaches to information provision and service design? What is the relative importance of strong and weak kinship ties (Papangelis2014) to improved understanding of infrmation dispersion and the relative resilience, adaptability and vulnerability of different social segments? </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-3">
