      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-9">

        <h2>Argumentation Mining from Social Media Text</h2>
        <p>
        Description: Various reports (OECD) highlight the need for new technologies to facilitate the drawing of insights from social media. The field of text analytics has made rapid progress in some areas such as sentiment analysis, but little progress on more complex tasks such as argumentation mining, which could facilitate researchers and policy makers in better understanding why people hold the opinions they do. A key reason for this lack of progress is the lack of resources such as corpora to facilitate machine learning and text simplification software (Siddharthan2006). Such resurce building is the key aim of this reserch, which is relevant to two ESRC strategic priority areas: &acirc;&euro;&#339;influencing behaviour and informing interventions&acirc;&euro;&#157; and a &acirc;&euro;&#339;vibrant and fair society&acirc;&euro;&#157;, as well as wider strategic interest in converting data to knowledge. Previous work only considers a binary classification of sentences in legal documents as belonging to an argument or not and identifies high-level organizational elements in argumentative discourse. We will leverage resources from our previous work on argumentation schemes for science; e.g. for Citation Analysis and Argumentative Zoning. </p>

        <h3>Research Questions</h3>
        <p>
        How suitable is the Toulmin scheme for annotating arguentation in social media texts? Can a reliable scheme and annotation manual be developed for such texts? To what extent are linguistic and compuational resources developed for text simplification and analysing argumentation in science useful for argument mining in social media?
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-3">
