      <div class="col-sm-12 col-md-9">
        <h2>Provenance of Social Media Data</h2>
        <p>
        It has been widely recognized that the social science research community faces challenges associated with the reliability, statistical validity, and generalizability of data obtained from new sources, such as the Internet, which may raise qustions about the validity of research based on such data (OECD - Challenge 1). We argue that understanding the provenance of such data and its subsequent analysis could play a key role in addressing these challenges, by increasing transparency. This in turn could help improve the undestandability of the research, support assessment of analytical methods, and aid reproducibility (Cheney2012). This additional contextual information should also facilitate data reuse (OECD &acirc;&euro;&ldquo; Challenge 9). Our recent experience of defining and applying the W3C PROV standard in a number of application domains (Corsar2014), and developing eInfrastructure for the social scences, equips us with the necessary expertise to investigate provenance in the social media context.
        </p>

        <h3>Research Questions</h3>
        <p>
         What charcteristics of social media data should be captured to facilitate greater verification and reproducibility of research using such datasets? What are the appropriate conceptual models to describe these characteristics? How can existing prvenance models be employed to record the analyses performed using such social media data?
        </p>
      </div>
